Monday, 25 Sep 2006 </DIV><A id=3Dthoughts_on_an_opendocument_toolkit=20
name=3Dthoughts_on_an_opendocument_toolkit></A><A=20
href=3D"http://blogs.sun.com/GullFOSS/entry/thoughts_on_an_opendocument_t=
oolkit"><SPAN=20
class=3Dentrytitle>Thoughts on an OpenDocument Toolkit</SPAN></A><BR>
<DIV class=3Dentryheader>Michael Brauer</DIV>
<DIV class=3Dbody>
<P>Welcome to the readers of this new GullFOSS blog. I'm Michael Brauer, =

OpenOffice.org XML project lead and OASIS <A=20
href=3D"http://www.oasis-open.org/committees/tc_home.php?wg_abbrev=3Doffi=
ce">OpenDocument</A>=20
Technical Committee (TC) chair. I intend to blog here constantly, and my =
primary=20
topic for this blog will be OpenDocument (what else?).</P>
<P>In my first series of blogs I will write about the topic of =
OpenDocument=20
toolkits (in short ODF toolkits). That's a topic we (my colleagues at =
Sun's=20
OpenOffice.org team and myself) are working on for a long time already, =
and that=20
gets more and more attraction. It was for instance a topic at the <A=20
href=3D"http://marketing.openoffice.org/ooocon2006/index.html">OOoCon =
2006</A> in=20
Lyon last week, and my TC colleague <A =
href=3D"http://robweir.com/blog/">Robert=20
Weir</A>, whom I met in Lyon, posted a proposal for an ODF toolkit <A=20
href=3D"http://opendocument.xml.org/node/154">here</A> a couple of day =
ago. So, it=20
seems that the time has come to share our thoughts and experience with =
the=20
public.</P>
<P>First of all: What is an OpenDocument toolkit? In short, it is a =
framework=20
that has a standardized API and that allows the creation and =
manipulation of=20
OpenDocument files in a lightweight fashion outside office applications. =
This is=20
something that is demanded in a number of projects, and where we could =
gain=20
already some experience in (unfortunately non-public) customer projects, =
but=20
also in the OpenOffice.org development itself, for instance when =
developing=20
filter components. BTW: There are many synonymous names for an ODF =
toolkit, like=20
ODF framework, or ODF development kit, but I will only use the term=20
<EM>OpenDocument/ODF toolkit</EM> for toolkit itself, and the term=20
<EM>ODF/OpenDocument API</EM> for its APIs.</P>
<P>When designing ODF APIs, and when implementing an ODF toolkit, where =
are a=20
couple of aspects that have to be considered. For instance:</P>
<UL style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25in">
  <LI>
  <P>The languages bindings: Shall it be a programming language specific =
API=20
  (for instance a Java API), or an API that provides multiple language=20
  bindings.</P>
  <LI>
  <P>The "scope" of the API: What are the classes of use cases that can =
be=20
  implemented using the API. Examples are APIs for creating OpenDocument =

  documents from scratch, APIs for filling existing documents with =
(customer or=20
  use case specific) data, APIs for conversion of documents from and to =
other=20
  formats, etc. Each of these use cases has its own requirements.</P>
  <LI>
  <P>The abstraction level of the API. The range starts here with =
low-level APIs=20
  similar to DOM or SAX, and ends with high-level APIs which offer a =
high level=20
  of abstraction from the (OpenDocument) XML that is saved in =
files.</P></LI></UL>
<P>Beside this pure API related questions, we also have to take into =
account the=20
interoperability with supplemental components, like OpenDocument =
viewers. One=20
may actually consider them to be part of a toolkit, but I think its =
better to=20
examine them separately, because they can be used with or without the =
API and=20
framework we are discussing here. The ODF Viewer plug-in for Firefox =
that we=20
have implemented for instance can be used for viewing documents created =
using an=20
ODF toolkit, but of course also can view documents created by one of the =
ODF=20
office applications, like OpenOffice.org or KOffice.</P>
<P>It goes beyond the scope of a single blog entry to discuss all of =
these=20
topics. I'm therefore concentrating today on the language bindings, and =
will=20
come back to some of the other topics in follow-up postings (in about =
two weeks,=20
because I will be in vacation for about a week now).</P>
<P>The question regarding the language binding is whether the API should =
be an=20
API for a specific programming language (like Java or C++), or whether =
it should=20
be an programming-language independent API that supports bindings for =
multiple=20
programming languages, like Java, C/C++, Phyton, etc. There may be =
exceptions=20
for some low-level APIs, but I think in general it's important that an =
ODF-API=20
provides bindings for all these languages. Java for instance is required =
because=20
it in my point of view is <I>the</I> programming language for XML based=20
application if we take declarative languages like XSLT aside. C/C++ is =
required=20
because that's the programming language most (ODF aware) office =
applications are=20
implemented in. So, if we want that the lightweight toolkit and office=20
applications can share components, we need these multiple bindings.</P>
<P>Actually, the language binding issue is not new and not related to an =
ODF=20
API, but applies to all APIs. The OpenOffice.org project, being a =
platform=20
independent project, has to deal with this situation for may years now, =
and has=20
developed a technology called <A =
href=3D"http://udk.openoffice.org/">UNO</A> to=20
open its APIs to many programming languages and platforms. The following =

description is taken from <A =
href=3D"http://udk.openoffice.org/">OpenOfffice.org=20
web page</A> directly:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>UNO (<STRONG>U</STRONG>niversal <STRONG>N</STRONG>etwork=20
  <STRONG>O</STRONG>bjects) is the interface-based component model of=20
  OpenOffice.org. It offers interoperability between different =
programming=20
  languages, different object models, different machine architectures =
and=20
  different processes; either in a local network or even via the =
Internet. UNO=20
  components can be implemented in and accessed from any programming =
language=20
  for which a UNO language binding exists. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Currently, that's Java, C++ and Phyton. Some more bindings are =
available that=20
support the access to components, but cannot be used for component=20
development.</P>
<P>UNO is used by OpenOffice.org to achieve platform and language =
independence,=20
but it also available stand-alone as so called <A=20
href=3D"http://download.openoffice.org/680/ure.html">UNO Runtime =
Environment=20
(URE)</A>. So, it would be available for use in an OpenDocument toolkit =
without=20
adding any of the OpenOffice.org code itself to the toolkit. UNO further =
has=20
proven its value in real life already. For this reason, it seems to be a =
solid=20
basis whenever an API of the OpenDocument toolkit shall be platform and=20
programming language independent. </P>
<P>That's it for today. If you like, stay tuned for my follow-up =
postings in=20
about two weeks.</P>
<P align=3Dright><SMALL>tags: </SMALL></P></DIV>
